Whoever posted &quot;The Elusive Enemy&quot; topic is really good!<br><br>
You are to be complimented for your ability to get at tough issues.<br><br>
I'll bite.<br><br>
I feel there are really many elusive enemies in the Vietnam War context.<br><br>
1. The combatant enemy was a shrewd soldier using tactics invented by American Revolutionary Soldiers on contemporary American Soldiers. Here, and not here. Everywhere, and nowhere. I guess I know what the Red Coats felt being randomly ambushed from behind stone walls on the &quot;Battle Road&quot;. We wouldn't stand up and fight in rows and columns like &quot;civilized&quot; people in 1776. <br><br>
2. A second elusive enemy can be considered to be incompetance in command that exacerbated an already bad combat situation.<br><br>
3. The propaganda force on the pro and con sides of the war can be considered a third elusive enemy.<br><br>
4. The last elusive enemy is that thing that many of us still carry in our heads.<br><br>
Those are my thoughts.
